column9: This volume serves as the primary record for a number of important excavations undertaken in the 1970s and 1980s by the Lincoln Archaeological Trust and the City of Lincoln Archaeological Unit. THe excavations were typically undertaken in a rescue environment ahead of planned development, and as such many were not effectively written up. The volume is the result of a collaboration between the City of Lincoln Council and Historic England to ensure that the archives of these excavations were properly stored and that a narrative of the sites could be prepared and published.

column9: Report on a scheme of works on land off St. Botolph's Crescent. Following evaluation, the developer undertook foundation excavations without benefit of archaeological supervision. The scheme of works was therefore limited to cleaning and recording the sides foundation trenches. THis revealed several ditches and pits, an assemblage of 13th/14th century pottery, and quantities of cattle horn cores. These latter remains may be indicative of medieval tanning and horn working on or near the site.

column9: Report on an excavation undertaken on land off Newport, Lincoln, in advance of the construction of a residential development. THe excavation recovered evidence of multiple periods, but is most notable for the Roman funerary remains identified. These included 8 inhumation burials, of which one was possibly contained within a possible mausolem structure. This is so far unique in Lincoln, although not unusual for a major Roman city. This perhaps indicates that further such monuments remain to be found in the surrounding area.

column9: A report on archaeological monitoring and recording during the development of land at 37-39 St Catherine's, Lincoln. Although no structural remains associated with the former Priory were encountered, a potential robber trench indicates the presence of a building at some point. The development also cut through a graveyard soil in which four in situ adult inhumations were recorded, along with the disarticulated remains of at least five other individuals.
